G-7b (the Quake gate, TAPESTRY.md section 9/18.9) -- guard
S_ClearOverflow against an un-allocated known_sfx.

With -nosound (no virtio-sound driver exists at v1.0, TAPESTRY.md
section 10 item 4), S_Init returns at its first line BEFORE allocating
`known_sfx` (a static pointer, snd_dma.c:75, allocated only at
snd_dma.c:214). But Host_ClearMemory calls S_ClearOverflow
unconditionally on every level load (host.c:474), and S_ClearOverflow
dereferences `known_sfx->overflow` with NO guard -- while its siblings
S_StopAllSounds and S_ClearBuffer both bail on `!sound_started`. The
result is a NULL deref (snare:segv addr=0xb008, the ->overflow field
offset) the instant the demo loads its first map. Upstream simply
omits the guard its neighbours carry; the fix mirrors them.

Applied to a build-dir COPY of the vendored tree (the SDL2/musl idiom;
third_party/tyrquake stays byte-pristine).
--- a/common/snd_dma.c
+++ b/common/snd_dma.c
@@ -279,6 +279,14 @@
 void
 S_ClearOverflow()
 {
+    /* pouch (G-7b): guard like S_StopAllSounds / S_ClearBuffer. With
+     * -nosound (no virtio-sound at v1.0) S_Init returns before it
+     * allocates known_sfx, but Host_ClearMemory calls this on every
+     * level load -- the unguarded known_sfx->overflow deref NULL-
+     * faults. Upstream lacks the guard its siblings carry. */
+    if (!snd_initialized || !known_sfx)
+	return;
+
     S_StopAllSounds(true);
     struct known_sfx *known = known_sfx->overflow;
 
--- a/common/sys_unix.c
+++ b/common/sys_unix.c
@@ -362,6 +362,12 @@
     signal(SIGFPE, SIG_IGN);
 #endif
 
+    /* pouch (G-7b): unbuffered stdout so Con_Printf progress reaches the
+     * serial tee in real time (the NQ path's Sys_Printf never fflushes;
+     * block buffering otherwise hides the whole boot behind the crash/
+     * exit flush). */
+    setvbuf(stdout, NULL, _IONBF, 0);
+
     memset(&parms, 0, sizeof(parms));
 
     COM_InitArgv(argc, (const char **)argv);
